# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sd-wan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] NFV relies upon traditional server-virtualization techniques, such as those used in enterprise IT.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] For example, a virtual session border controller could be deployed to protect a network without the typical cost and complexity of obtaining and installing physical network protection units.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Other examples of NFV include virtualized load balancers, firewalls, intrusion detection devices and WAN accelerators to name a few.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Decoupling the network function software from the customized hardware platform creates a flexible network architecture that enables agile network management, faster new service roll outs with significant reduction in CAPEX and OPEX.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Product development within the telecommunication industry has traditionally followed rigorous standards for stability, protocol adherence and quality, reflected by the use of the term carrier grade to designate equipment demonstrating this high reliability and performance factor.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] While this model worked well in the past, it inevitably led to long product cycles, a slow pace of development and reliance on proprietary or specific hardware, e.g., bespoke application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] In October 2012, a group of telecom operators published a white paper at a conference in Darmstadt, Germany, on software-defined networking (SDN) and OpenFlow.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The Call for Action concluding the White Paper led to the creation of the Network Functions Virtualization (NFV) Industry Specification Group (ISG) within the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The ISG was made up of representatives from the telecommunication industry from Europe and beyond.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] ETSI ISG NFV addresses many aspects, including functional architecture, information model, data model, protocols, APIs, testing, reliability, security, future evolutions, etc.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The ETSI ISG NFV has announced the Release 5 of its specifications since May 2021 aiming to produce new specifications and extend the already published specifications based on new features and enhancements.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Since the publication of the white paper, the group has produced over 100 publications, which have gained wider acceptance in the industry and are being implemented in prominent open source projects like OpenStack, ONAP, Open Source MANO (OSM) to name a few.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Due to active cross-liaison activities, the ETSI NFV specifications are also being referenced in other SDOs like 3GPP, IETF, ETSI MEC etc.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Network functions virtualization infrastructure (NFVI) is the totality of all hardware and software components that build the environment where NFVs are deployed.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The NFV infrastructure can span several locations.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The network providing connectivity between these locations is considered as part of the NFV infrastructure.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The building block for both the NFVI and the NFV-MANO is the NFV platform.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] In the NFVI role, it consists of both virtual and physical processing and storage resources, and virtualization software.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] In its NFV-MANO role it consists of VNF and NFVI managers and virtualization software operating on a hardware controller.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform implements carrier-grade features used to manage and monitor the platform components, recover from failures and provide effective security – all required for the public carrier network.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] A service provider that follows the NFV design implements one or more virtualized network functions, or *VNFs*.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] A VNF by itself does not automatically provide a usable product or service to the provider's customers.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] To build more complex services, the notion of *service chaining* is used, where multiple VNFs are used in sequence to deliver a service.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Another aspect of implementing NFV is the *orchestration* process.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] To build highly reliable and scalable services, NFV requires that the network be able to instantiate VNF instances, monitor them, repair them, and (most important for a service provider business) bill for the services rendered.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] These attributes, referred to as carrier-grade features, are allocated to an orchestration layer in order to provide high availability and security, and low operation and maintenance costs.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Importantly, the orchestration layer must be able to manage VNFs irrespective of the underlying technology within the VNF.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] For example, an orchestration layer must be able to manage an SBC VNF from vendor X running on VMware vSphere just as well as an IMS VNF from vendor Y running on KVM.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The initial perception of NFV was that virtualized capability should be implemented in data centers.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] This approach works in many – but not all – cases.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] NFV presumes and emphasizes the widest possible flexibility as to the physical location of the virtualized functions.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Ideally, therefore, virtualized functions should be located where they are the most effective and least expensive.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] That means a service provider should be free to locate NFV in all possible locations, from the data center to the network node to the customer premises.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] This approach, known as distributed NFV, has been emphasized from the beginning as NFV was being developed and standardized, and is prominent in the recently released NFV ISG documents.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] For some cases there are clear advantages for a service provider to locate this virtualized functionality at the customer premises.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] These advantages range from economics to performance to the feasibility of the functions being virtualized.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The first ETSI NFV ISG-approved public multi-vendor proof of concept (PoC) of D-NFV was conducted by Cyan, Inc., RAD, Fortinet and Certes Networks in Chicago in June, 2014, and was sponsored by CenturyLink.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] It was based on RAD's dedicated customer-edge D-NFV equipment running Fortinet's Next Generation Firewall (NGFW) and Certes Networks’ virtual encryption/decryption engine as Virtual Network Functions (VNFs) with Cyan's Blue Planet system orchestrating the entire ecosystem.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] RAD's D-NFV solution, a Layer 2/Layer 3 network termination unit (NTU) equipped with a D-NFV X86 server module that functions as a virtualization engine at the customer edge, became commercially available by the end of that month.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] During 2014 RAD also had organized a D-NFV Alliance, an ecosystem of vendors and international systems integrators specializing in new NFV applications.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] When designing and developing the software that provides the VNFs, vendors may structure that software into software components (implementation view of a software architecture) and package those components into one or more images (deployment view of a software architecture).
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] These vendor-defined software components are called VNF Components (VNFCs).
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] VNFs are implemented with one or more VNFCs and it is assumed, without loss of generality, that VNFC instances map 1:1 to VM Images.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] VNFCs should in general be able to scale up and/or scale out.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] By being able to allocate flexible (virtual) CPUs to each of the VNFC instances, the network management layer can scale up (i.e., scale *vertically*) the VNFC to provide the throughput/performance and scalability expectations over a single system or a single platform.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Similarly, the network management layer can scale out (i.e., *scale horizontally*) a VNFC by activating multiple instances of such VNFC over multiple platforms and therefore reach out to the performance and architecture specifications whilst not compromising the other VNFC function stabilities.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Network Functions Virtualisation is highly complementary to SDN.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] In essence, SDN is an approach to building data networking equipment and software that separates and abstracts elements of these systems.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] It does this by decoupling the control plane and data plane from each other, such that the control plane resides centrally and the forwarding components remain distributed.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The control plane interacts with both northbound and southbound.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] In the northbound direction the control plane provides a common abstracted view of the network to higher-level applications and programs using high-level APIs and novel management paradigms, such as Intent-based networking.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] In the southbound direction the control plane programs the forwarding behavior of the data plane, using device level APIs of the physical network equipment distributed around the network.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts, but NFV and SDN can cooperate to enhance the management of a NFV infrastructure and to create a more dynamic network environment.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] An NFV system needs a central orchestration and management system that takes operator requests associated with an NS or a VNF, translates them into the appropriate processing, storage and network configuration needed to bring the NS or VNF into operation.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Once in operation, the VNF and the networks it is connected to potentially must be monitored for capacity and utilization, and adapted if necessary.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] All network control functions in an NFV infrastructure can be accomplished using SDN concepts and NFV could be considered one of the primary SDN use cases in service provider environments.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] For example, within each NFV infrastructure site, a VIM could rely upon an SDN controller to set up and configure the overlay networks interconnecting (e.g.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] VXLAN) the VNFs and PNFs composing an NS.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The SDN controller would then configure the NFV infrastructure switches and routers, as well as the network gateways, as needed.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Similarly, a Wide Area Infrastructure Manager (WIM) could rely upon an SDN controller to set up overlay networks to interconnect NSs that are deployed to different geo-located NFV infrastructures.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] It is also apparent that many SDN use-cases could incorporate concepts introduced in the NFV initiative.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Examples include where the centralized controller is controlling a distributed forwarding function that could in fact be also virtualized on existing processing or routing equipment.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] NFV has proven a popular standard even in its infancy.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Its immediate applications are numerous, such as virtualization of mobile base stations, platform as a service (PaaS), content delivery networks (CDN), fixed access and home environments.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The potential benefits of NFV is anticipated to be significant.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Virtualization of network functions deployed on general purpose standardized hardware is expected to reduce capital and operational expenditures, and service and product introduction times.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Many major network equipment vendors have announced support for NFV.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] This has coincided with NFV announcements from major software suppliers who provide the NFV platforms used by equipment suppliers to build their NFV products.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] However, to realize the anticipated benefits of virtualization, network equipment vendors are improving IT virtualization technology to incorporate carrier-grade attributes required to achieve high availability, scalability, performance, and effective network management capabilities.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] To minimize the total cost of ownership (TCO), carrier-grade features must be implemented as efficiently as possible.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] This requires that NFV solutions make efficient use of redundant resources to achieve five-nines availability (99.999%), and of computing resource without compromising performance predictability.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform is the foundation for achieving efficient carrier-grade NFV solutions.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] It is a software platform running on standard multi-core hardware and built using open source software that incorporates carrier-grade features.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform software is responsible for dynamically reassigning VNFs due to failures and changes in traffic load, and therefore plays an important role in achieving high availability.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] There are numerous initiatives underway to specify, align and promote NFV carrier-grade capabilities such as ETSI NFV Proof of Concept, ATIS Open Platform for NFV Project, Carrier Network Virtualization Awards and various supplier ecosystems.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The vSwitch, a key component of NFV platforms, is responsible for providing connectivity both VM-to-VM (between VMs) and between VMs and the outside network.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Its performance determines both the bandwidth of the VNFs and the cost-efficiency of NFV solutions.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The standard Open vSwitch's (OVS) performance has shortcomings that must be resolved to meet the needs of NFVI solutions.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Significant performance improvements are being reported by NFV suppliers for both OVS and Accelerated Open vSwitch (AVS) versions.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Virtualization is also changing the way availability is specified, measured and achieved in NFV solutions.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] As VNFs replace traditional function-dedicated equipment, there is a shift from equipment-based availability to a service-based, end-to-end, layered approach.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Virtualizing network functions breaks the explicit coupling with specific equipment, therefore availability is defined by the availability of VNF services.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Because NFV technology can virtualize a wide range of network function types, each with their own service availability expectations, NFV platforms should support a wide range of fault tolerance options.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] This flexibility enables CSPs to optimize their NFV solutions to meet any VNF availability requirement.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] ETSI has already indicated that an important part of controlling the NFV environment be done through automated orchestration.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] NFV Management and Orchestration (NFV-MANO) refers to a set of functions within an NFV system to manage and orchestrate the allocation of virtual infrastructure resources to virtualized network functions (VNFs) and network services (NSs).
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] They are the brains of the NFV system and a key automation enabler.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The entry point in NFV-MANO for external operations support systems (OSS) and business support systems (BSS) is the NFVO, which is in charge of managing the lifecycle of NS instances.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The management of the lifecycle of VNF instances constituting an NS instance is delegated by the NFVO to one more or VNFMs.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Both the NFVO and the VNFMs uses the services exposed by one or more VIMs for allocating virtual infrastructure resources to the objects they manage.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Additional functions are used for managing containerized VNFs: the Container Infrastructure Service Management (CISM) and the Container Image Registry (CIR) functions.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The CISM is responsible for maintaining the containerized workloads while the CIR is responsible for storing and maintaining information of OS container software images The behavior of the NFVO and VNFM is driven by the contents of deployment templates (a.k.a.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] NFV descriptors) such as a Network Service Descriptor (NSD) and a VNF Descriptor (VNFD).
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] ETSI delivers a full set of standards **enabling an open ecosystem** where Virtualized Network Functions (VNFs) can be interoperable with independently developed management and orchestration systems, and where the components of a management and orchestration system are themselves interoperable.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] This includes a set of Restful API specifications as well as the specifications of a packaging format for delivering VNFs to service providers and of the deployment templates to be packaged with the software images to enable managing the lifecycle of VNFs.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Deployment templates can be based on TOSCA or YANG.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Swagger) representation of the API specifications is available and maintained on the ETSI forge server, along with TOSCA and YANG definition files to be used when creating deployment templates.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The full set of published specifications is summarized in the table below.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] An overview of the different versions of the OpenAPI representations of NFV-MANO APIs is available on the ETSI NFV wiki.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] The OpenAPI files as well as the TOSCA YAML definition files and YANG modules applicable to NFV descriptors are available on the ETSI Forge.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Recent performance study on NFV focused on the throughput, latency and jitter of virtualized network functions (VNFs), as well as NFV scalability in terms of the number of VNFs a single physical server can support.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] From 2018, many VNF providers began to migrate many of their VNFs to a container-based architecture.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Such VNFs also known as Cloud-Native Network Functions (CNF) utilize many innovations deployed commonly on internet infrastructure.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] These include auto-scaling, supporting a continuous delivery / DevOps deployment model, and efficiency gains by sharing common services across platforms.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Through service discovery and orchestration, a network based on CNFs will be more resilient to infrastructure resource failures.
[src:sd-wan/network-function-virtualization] Utilizing containers, and thus dispensing with the overhead inherent in traditional virtualization through the elimination of the guest OS can greatly increase infrastructure resource efficiency.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] An **overlay network** is a logical computer network that is layered on top of a physical network.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] The concept of overlay networking is distinct from the traditional model of OSI layered networks, and almost always assumes that the underlay network is an IP network of some kind.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Some examples of overlay networking technologies are, VXLAN, BGP VPNs, and IP-over-IP technologies, such as GRE, IPSEC tunnels, or SD-WAN.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Nodes in an overlay network can be thought of as being connected by logical links, each of which corresponds to a path, perhaps through many physical links, in the underlying network.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] For example, distributed systems such as peer-to-peer networks are overlay networks because their nodes form networks over existing network connections.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] The Internet was originally built as an overlay upon the telephone network, while today (through the advent of VoIP), the telephone network is increasingly turning into an overlay network built on top of the Internet.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Overlay networks have a certain set of attributes, including separation of logical addressing, security and quality of service.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Other optional attributes include resiliency, encryption and bandwidth control.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Guaranteeing bandwidth through marking traffic has multiple solutions, including IntServ and DiffServ.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] IntServ requires per-flow tracking and consequently causes scaling issues in routing platforms.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] DiffServ has been widely deployed in many operators as a method to differentiate traffic types.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] DiffServ itself provides no guarantee of throughput; it does allow the network operator to decide which traffic is higher priority, and hence will be forwarded first in congestion situations.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Overlay networks implement a much finer granularity of quality of service, allowing enterprise users to decide on an application and user or site basis which traffic should be prioritized.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Many telcos use overlay networks to provide services over their physical infrastructure.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] In the networks that connect physically diverse sites (wide area networks, WANs), one common overlay network technology is BGP VPNs.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] These VPNs are provided in the form of a service to enterprises to connect their own sites and applications.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] The advantage of these kinds of overlay networks is that the telecom operator does not need to manage addressing or other enterprise-specific network attributes.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] From an enterprise point of view, while an overlay VPN service configured by the operator might fulfill their basic connectivity requirements, SD-WAN overlay networks offer additional flexibility.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] The Internet is the basis for more overlaid networks that can be constructed in order to permit routing of messages to destinations not specified by an IP address.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] For example, distributed hash tables can be used to route messages to a node having a specific logical address, whose IP address is not known in advance.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Overlay networks can be incrementally deployed at end-user sites or on hosts running the overlay protocol software, without cooperation from Internet service providers.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] The overlay has no control over how packets are routed in the underlying network between two overlay nodes, but it can control, for example, the sequence of overlay nodes a message traverses before reaching its destination.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] The objective of resilience in telecommunications networks is to enable automated recovery during failure events in order to maintain a wanted service level or availability.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] As telecommunications networks are built in a layered fashion, resilience can be used in the physical, optical, IP or session to application layers.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Each layer relies on the resilience features of the layer below it.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Overlay IP networks in the form of SD-WAN services therefore rely on the physical, optical and underlying IP services they are transported over.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Application-layer overlays depend on all the layers below them.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] The advantage of overlays is that they are more flexible and programmable than traditional network infrastructure, which can outweigh the disadvantages of additional latency, complexity and bandwidth overheads.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] The limited deployment of IP multicast, a best-effort network-layer multicast protocol, has led to considerable interest in alternate approaches that are implemented at the application layer in accordance with the end-to-end principle.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] In an overlay or end-system multicast approach, participating peers organize themselves into an overlay topology for data delivery.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] Each edge in this topology corresponds to a unicast path between two end-systems or peers in the underlying internet.
[src:sd-wan/overlay-network] All multicast-related functionality is implemented at the peers instead of at routers, and the goal of the multicast protocol is to construct and maintain an efficient overlay for data transmission.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, quality of service refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Quality of service is the ability to provide different priorities to different applications, users, or data flows, or to guarantee a certain level of performance to a data flow.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Quality of service is particularly important for the transport of traffic with special requirements, including voice over IP and other audio networking techniques, professional video over IP, card-based payments, and real-time computing.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In the field of telephony, quality of service was defined by the ITU in 1994.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Quality of service comprises requirements on all the aspects of a connection, such as service response time, loss, signal-to-noise ratio, crosstalk, echo, interrupts, frequency response, loudness levels, and so on.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] A subset of telephony QoS is grade of service (GoS) requirements, which comprises aspects of a connection relating to capacity and coverage of a network, for example, guaranteed maximum blocking probability and outage probability.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, teletraffic engineering refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] For example, a required bit rate, delay, delay variation, packet loss or bit error rates may be guaranteed.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Quality of service is important for real-time streaming multimedia applications such as voice over IP, multiplayer online games and IPTV, since these often require a fixed bit rate and are delay sensitive.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Quality of service is especially important in networks where the capacity is a limited resource, for example, in cellular data communication.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] A network or protocol that supports QoS may agree on a traffic contract with the application software and reserve capacity in the network nodes, for example during a session establishment phase.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] During the session, it may monitor the achieved level of performance, for example, the data rate and delay, and dynamically control scheduling priorities in the network nodes.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] It may release the reserved capacity during a tear down phase.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] A best-effort network or service does not support quality of service.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication over a best-effort network by over-provisioning the capacity so that it is sufficient for the expected peak traffic load.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The resulting absence of network congestion reduces or eliminates the need for QoS mechanisms.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used as a quality measure, with many alternative definitions, rather than referring to the ability to reserve resources.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Quality of service sometimes refers to the level of quality of service, i.e. the guaranteed service quality.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] High QoS is often confused with a high level of performance, for example high bit rate, low latency and low bit error rate.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used in application layer services such as telephony and streaming video to describe a metric that reflects or predicts the subjectively experienced quality.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In this context, QoS is the acceptable cumulative effect on subscriber satisfaction of all imperfections affecting the service.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Other terms with similar meaning are the quality of experience (QoE), mean opinion score (MOS), perceptual speech quality measure (PSQM) and perceptual evaluation of video quality (PEVQ).
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] A number of attempts for layer 2 technologies that add QoS tags to the data have gained popularity in the past.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Examples are Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) (a technique between layer 2 and 3).
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Despite these network technologies remaining in use today, this kind of network lost attention after the advent of Ethernet networks.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Today, Ethernet is, by far, the most popular layer 2 technology.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Conventional Internet routers and network switches operate on a best-effort basis.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] This equipment is less expensive, less complex and faster and thus more popular than earlier, more complex technologies that provide QoS mechanisms.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Ethernet optionally uses 802.1p to signal the priority of a frame.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] There were four *type of service* bits and three *precedence* bits originally provided in each IP packet header, but they were not generally respected.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] These bits were later re-defined as Differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] With the advent of IPTV and IP telephony, QoS mechanisms are increasingly available to the end user.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In packet-switched networks, quality of service is affected by various factors, which can be divided into human and technical factors.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Human factors include: stability of service quality, availability of service, waiting times and user information.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Technical factors include: reliability, scalability, effectiveness, maintainability and network congestion.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Due to varying load from disparate users sharing the same network resources, the maximum throughput that can be provided to a certain data stream may be too low for real-time multimedia services.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The network may fail to deliver (*drop*) some packets due to network congestion.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The receiving application may ask for this information to be retransmitted, possibly resulting in congestive collapse or unacceptable delays in the overall transmission.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Sometimes packets are corrupted due to bit errors caused by noise and interference, especially in wireless communications and long copper wires.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The receiver has to detect this, and, just as if the packet was dropped, may ask for this information to be retransmitted.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] It might take a long time for each packet to reach its destination because it gets held up in long queues, or it takes a less direct route to avoid congestion.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In some cases, excessive latency can render an application such as VoIP or online gaming unusable.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Packets from the source will reach the destination with different delays.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] A packet's delay varies with its position in the queues of the routers along the path between source and destination, and this position can vary unpredictably.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Delay variation can be absorbed at the receiver, but in so doing increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] When a collection of related packets is routed through a network, different packets may take different routes, each resulting in a different delay.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The result is that the packets arrive in a different order than they were sent.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] This problem requires special additional protocols for rearranging out-of-order packets.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The reordering process requires additional buffering at the receiver, and, as with packet delay variation, increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] These types of service are called *inelastic*, meaning that they require a certain minimum bit rate and a certain maximum latency to function.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] By contrast, *elastic* applications can take advantage of however much or little bandwidth is available.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Bulk file transfer applications that rely on TCP are generally elastic.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Circuit-switched networks, especially those intended for voice transmission, such as ATM or GSM, have QoS in the core protocol; resources are reserved at each step on the network for the call as it is set up, and there is no need for additional procedures to achieve the required performance.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Shorter data units and built-in QoS were some of the unique selling points of ATM for applications such as video on demand.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication by generously over-provisioning a network so that capacity is based on peak traffic load estimates.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] This approach is simple for networks with predictable peak loads.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] This calculation may need to appreciate demanding applications that can compensate for variations in bandwidth and delay with large receive buffers, which is often possible, for example, in video streaming.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Over-provisioning can be of limited use in the face of transport protocols (such as TCP) that, over time, increase the amount of data placed on the network until all available bandwidth is consumed and packets are dropped.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Such greedy protocols tend to increase latency and packet loss for all users.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The amount of over-provisioning in interior links required to replace QoS depends on the number of users and their traffic demands.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] This limits the usability of over-provisioning.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Newer, more bandwidth-intensive applications and the addition of more users result in the loss of over-provisioned networks.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] This then requires a physical update of the relevant network links, which is an expensive process.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Thus, over-provisioning cannot be blindly assumed on the Internet.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Commercial VoIP services are often competitive with traditional telephone service in terms of call quality, even without QoS mechanisms in use on the user's connection to their ISP and the VoIP provider's connection to a different ISP.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Under high load conditions, however, VoIP may degrade to cell-phone quality or worse.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The mathematics of packet traffic indicates that the network requires just 60% more raw capacity under conservative assumptions.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Unlike single-owner networks, the Internet is a series of exchange points interconnecting private networks.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Hence the Internet's core is owned and managed by a number of different network service providers, not a single entity.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Its behavior is much more unpredictable.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] There are two principal approaches to QoS in modern packet-switched IP networks: a parameterized system based on an exchange of application requirements with the network, and a prioritized system where each packet identifies a desired service level to the network.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Early work used the integrated services (IntServ) philosophy of reserving network resources.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In this model, applications used RSVP to request and reserve resources through a network.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] While IntServ mechanisms do work, it was realized that in a broadband network typical of a larger service provider, Core routers would be required to accept, maintain, and tear down thousands or possibly tens of thousands of reservations.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] It was believed that this approach would not scale with the growth of the Internet, and in any event was antithetical to the end-to-end principle, the notion of designing networks so that core routers do little more than simply switch packets at the highest possible rates.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Under DiffServ, packets are marked either by the traffic sources themselves or by the edge devices where the traffic enters the network.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In response to these markings, routers and switches use various queuing strategies to tailor performance to requirements.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] At the IP layer, DSCP markings use the 6-bit DS field in the IP packet header.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] At the MAC layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q can be used to carry 3 bits of essentially the same information.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Routers and switches supporting DiffServ configure their network scheduler to use multiple queues for packets awaiting transmission from bandwidth-constrained (e.g., wide area) interfaces.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Router vendors provide different capabilities for configuring this behavior, including the number of queues supported, the relative priorities of queues, and the bandwidth reserved for each queue.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In practice, when a packet must be forwarded from an interface with queuing, packets requiring low jitter (e.g., VoIP or videoconferencing) are given priority over packets in other queues.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Typically, some bandwidth is allocated by default to network control packets (such as Internet Control Message Protocol and routing protocols), while best-effort traffic might simply be given whatever bandwidth is left over.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] At the medium access control (MAC) layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q and IEEE 802.1p can be used to distinguish between Ethernet frames and classify them.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Queueing theory models have been developed on performance analysis and QoS for MAC layer protocols.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Cisco IOS NetFlow and the Cisco Class Based QoS (CBQoS) Management Information Base (MIB) are marketed by Cisco Systems.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] One compelling example of the need for QoS on the Internet relates to congestive collapse.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The Internet relies on congestion avoidance protocols, primarily as built into Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), to reduce traffic under conditions that would otherwise lead to congestive collapse.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] QoS applications, such as VoIP and IPTV, require largely constant bitrates and low latency, therefore they cannot use TCP and cannot otherwise reduce their traffic rate to help prevent congestion.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Service-level agreements limit traffic that can be offered to the Internet and thereby enforce traffic shaping that can prevent it from becoming overloaded, and are hence an indispensable part of the Internet's ability to handle a mix of real-time and non-real-time traffic without collapse.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Several QoS mechanisms and schemes exist for IP networking.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] QoS capabilities are available in the following network technologies.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] End-to-end quality of service can require a method of coordinating resource allocation between one autonomous system and another.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for bandwidth reservation as a proposed standard in 1997.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] RSVP is an end-to-end bandwidth reservation and admission control protocol.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] RSVP was not widely adopted due to scalability limitations.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The more scalable traffic engineering version, RSVP-TE, is used in many networks to establish traffic-engineered Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched paths.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The IETF also defined Next Steps in Signaling (NSIS) with QoS signalling as a target.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] NSIS is a development and simplification of RSVP.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Research consortia such as "end-to-end quality of service support over heterogeneous networks" (EuQoS, from 2004 through 2007) and fora such as the IPsphere Forum developed more mechanisms for handshaking QoS invocation from one domain to the next.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] IPsphere defined the Service Structuring Stratum (SSS) signaling bus in order to establish, invoke and (attempt to) assure network services.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] EuQoS conducted experiments to integrate Session Initiation Protocol, Next Steps in Signaling and IPsphere's SSS with an estimated cost of about 15.6 million Euro and published a book.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] A research project Multi Service Access Everywhere (MUSE) defined another QoS concept in a first phase from January 2004 through February 2006, and a second phase from January 2006 through 2007.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Another research project named PlaNetS was proposed for European funding circa 2005.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] A broader European project called "Architecture and design for the future Internet" known as 4WARD had a budget estimated at 23.4 million Euro and was funded from January 2008 through June 2010.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] It included a "Quality of Service Theme" and published a book.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Another European project, called WIDENS (Wireless Deployable Network System), proposed a bandwidth reservation approach for mobile wireless multirate adhoc networks.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Strong cryptography network protocols such as Secure Sockets Layer, I2P, and virtual private networks obscure the data transferred using them.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] As all electronic commerce on the Internet requires the use of such strong cryptography protocols, unilaterally downgrading the performance of encrypted traffic creates an unacceptable hazard for customers.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Yet, encrypted traffic is otherwise unable to undergo deep packet inspection for QoS.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Protocols like ICA and RDP may encapsulate other traffic (e.g. printing, video streaming) with varying requirements that can make optimization difficult.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The Internet2 project found, in 2001, that the QoS protocols were probably not deployable inside its Abilene Network with equipment available at that time.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The group predicted that "logistical, financial, and organizational barriers will block the way toward any bandwidth guarantees" by protocol modifications aimed at QoS.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] They believed that the economics would encourage network providers to deliberately erode the quality of best effort traffic as a way to push customers to higher-priced QoS services.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Instead, they proposed over-provisioning of capacity as more cost-effective at the time.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The Abilene network study was the basis for the testimony of Gary Bachula to the US Senate Commerce Committee's hearing on Network Neutrality in early 2006.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] He expressed the opinion that adding more bandwidth was more effective than any of the various schemes for accomplishing QoS they examined.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Bachula's testimony has been cited by proponents of a law banning quality of service as proof that no legitimate purpose is served by such an offering.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] This argument is dependent on the assumption that over-provisioning isn't a form of QoS and that it is always possible.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Cost and other factors affect the ability of carriers to build and maintain permanently over-provisioned networks.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Mobile cellular service providers may offer mobile QoS to customers just as the wired public switched telephone network service providers and Internet service providers may offer QoS.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] QoS mechanisms are always provided for circuit switched services, and are essential for inelastic services, for example streaming multimedia.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Mobility adds complications to QoS mechanisms.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] A phone call or other session may be interrupted after a handover if the new base station is overloaded.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Unpredictable handovers make it impossible to give an absolute QoS guarantee during the session initiation phase.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Quality of service in the field of telephony was first defined in 1994 in ITU-T Recommendation E.800.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] This definition is very broad, listing 6 primary components: Support, Operability, Accessibility, Retainability, Integrity and Security.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] In 1998 the ITU published a document discussing QoS in the field of data networking.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] X.641 offers a means of developing or enhancing standards related to QoS and provides concepts and terminology that should assist in maintaining the consistency of related standards.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] Some QoS-related IETF Request for Comments (RFC)s are *Baker, Fred; Black, David L.; Nichols, Kathleen; Blake, Steven L.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] (December 1998), *Definition of the Differentiated services Field (DS Field) in the IPv4 and IPv6 Headers*, doi:10.17487/RFC2474, RFC 2474*, and *Braden, Robert T.; Zhang, Lixia; Berson, Steven; Herzog, Shai; Jamin, Sugih (September 1997), Braden, R.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] (ed.), *Resource ReSerVation Protocol (RSVP)*, doi:10.17487/RFC2205, RFC 2205*; both these are discussed above.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The IETF has also published two RFCs giving background on QoS: *Huston, Geoff (November 2000), *Next Steps for the IP QoS Architecture*, doi:10.17487/RFC2990, RFC 2990*, and *Floyd, S.; Kempf, J.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] (ed.), *IAB Concerns Regarding Congestion Control for Voice Traffic in the Internet*, doi:10.17487/RFC3714, RFC 3714*.
[src:sd-wan/quality-of-service] The document tries to identify applications commonly run over an IP network, groups them into traffic classes, studies the treatment required by these classes from the network, and suggests which of the QoS mechanisms commonly available in routers can be used to implement those treatments.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] A **Software-Defined Wide Area Network** (**SD-WAN**) is a wide area network that uses software-defined networking technology, such as communicating over the Internet using overlay tunnels which are encrypted when destined for internal organization locations.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] If standard tunnel setup and configuration messages are supported by all of the network hardware vendors, SD-WAN simplifies the management and operation of a WAN by decoupling the networking hardware from its control mechanism.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] This concept is similar to how software-defined networking implements virtualization technology to improve data center management and operation.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] In practice, proprietary protocols are used to set up and manage an SD-WAN, meaning there is no decoupling of the hardware and its control mechanism.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] A key application of SD-WAN is to allow companies to build higher-performance WANs using lower-cost and commercially available Internet access, enabling businesses to partially or wholly replace more expensive private WANs connection technologies such as MPLS.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] When SD-WAN traffic is carried over the Internet, there are no end-to-end performance guarantees.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Carrier MPLS VPN WAN services are not carried as Internet traffic, but rather over carefully controlled carrier capacity, and do come with an end-to-end performance guarantee.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] WANs were very important for the development of networking in general and for a long time one of the most important applications of networks both for military and enterprise applications.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] The ability to communicate data over long distances was one of the main driving factors for the development of data communications, as it made it possible to overcome the distance limitations, as well as shortening the time necessary to exchange messages with other parties.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Legacy WANs allowed communication over circuits connecting two or more endpoints.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Earlier networking supported point-to-point communication over a slow speed circuit, usually between two fixed locations.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] As networking progressed, WAN circuits became faster and more flexible.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Innovations like circuit and packet switching (in the form of X.25, ATM and later Internet Protocol or Multiprotocol Label Switching) allowed communication to become more dynamic, supporting ever-growing networks.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] The need for strict control, security and quality of service (QOS) meant that multinational corporations were very conservative in leasing and operating their WANs.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] National regulations restricted the companies that could provide local service in each country, and complex arrangements were necessary to establish truly global networks.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] All that changed with the growth of the Internet, which permitted entities around the world to connect to each other.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] However, over the first years, the uncontrolled nature of the Internet was not considered adequate or safe for private corporate use.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Independent of safety concerns, connectivity to the Internet became a necessity to the point where every branch required Internet access.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] At first, due to safety concerns, private communications were still done via WAN, and communication with other entities (including customers and partners) moved to the Internet.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] As the Internet grew in reach and maturity, companies started to evaluate how to leverage it for private corporate communications.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] During the early 2000s, application delivery over the WAN became an important topic of research and commercial innovation.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN combines several networking aspects to create full-fledged private networks, with the ability to dynamically share network bandwidth across the connection points.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Additional enhancements include central controllers, zero-touch provisioning, integrated analytics and on-demand circuit provisioning, with some network intelligence based in the cloud, allowing centralized policy management and security.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Networking publications started using the term SD-WAN to describe this new networking trend as early as 2014.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] With the rapid shift to remote work as a result of lockdowns and stay at home orders during the COVID-19 pandemic, SD-WAN grew in popularity as a way of connecting remote workers.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] WANs allow companies to extend their computer networks over large distances, connecting remote branch offices to data centers and to each other, and delivering applications and services required to perform business functions.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Modern applications such as VoIP calling, videoconferencing, streaming media, and virtualized applications and desktops require low latency.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Bandwidth requirements are also increasing, especially for applications featuring high-definition video.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] It can be expensive and difficult to expand WAN capability, with corresponding difficulties related to network management and troubleshooting.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN products are designed to address these network problems.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] By enhancing or even replacing traditional branch routers with virtualization appliances that can control application-level policies and offer a network overlay, less expensive consumer-grade Internet links can act more like a dedicated circuit.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] This simplifies the setup process for branch personnel.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN products can be physical appliances or software based only.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] The MEF Forum has defined an SD-WAN architecture consisting of an SD-WAN edge, SD-WAN gateway, SD-WAN controller and SD-WAN orchestrator.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] The SD-WAN edge is a physical or virtual network function that is placed at an organization's branch/regional/central office site, data center, and in public or private cloud platforms.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] MEF Forum has published the first SD-WAN service standard, MEF 70 which defines the fundamental characteristics of an SD-WAN service plus service requirements and attributes.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN gateways provide access to the SD-WAN service in order to shorten the distance to cloud-based services or the user, and reduce service interruptions.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] A distributed network of gateways may be included in an SD-WAN service by the vendor or setup and maintained by the organization using the service.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] By sitting outside the headquarters in the cloud, the gateway also reduces headquarters traffic.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] The SD-WAN orchestrator is a cloud hosted or on-premises web management tool that allows configuration, provisioning and other functions when operating an SD-WAN.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] It simplifies application traffic management by allowing central implementation of an organization's business policies.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] The SD-WAN controller functionality, which can be placed in the orchestrator or in an SD-WAN gateway, is used to make forwarding decisions for application flows.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Application flows are IP packets that have been classified to determine their user application or grouping of applications to which they are associated.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] The grouping of application flows based on a common type, e.g., conferencing applications, is referred to as an Application Flow Group in MEF 70.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] This helps ensure that application performance meets service level agreements (SLAs).
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Features of SD-WANs include resilience, quality of service (QoS), security, and performance, with flexible deployment options; simplified administration and troubleshooting; and online traffic engineering.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] A resilient SD-WAN reduces network downtime.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] To be resilient, the technology must feature real-time detection of outages and automatic switch over (fail over) to working links.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Many SD-WAN deployments use multiple network transports, including broadband, MPLS, and fixed wireless access, to maintain connectivity during outages or periods of degraded network performance.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN technology supports quality of service by having application level awareness, giving bandwidth priority to the most critical applications.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] This may include dynamic path selection, sending an application on a faster link, or even splitting an application between two paths to improve performance by delivering it faster.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN communication is usually secured using IPsec, a staple of WAN security.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WANs can improve application delivery using caching, storing recently accessed information in memory to speed future access.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WANs can incorporate *artificial intelligence for IT operations* (AIOps) for continuous troubleshooting and fixes to network issues.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Modern SD-WAN platforms may also use network analytics and real-time telemetry to improve traffic optimization, application visibility, and proactive issue detection across global enterprise environments.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Most SD-WAN products are available as pre-configured appliances, placed at the network edge in data centers, branch offices and other remote locations.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] There are also virtual appliances that can work on existing network hardware, or the appliance can be deployed as a virtual appliance on the cloud in environments such as Amazon Web Services (AWS), Unified Communications as a service (UCaaS) or as Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] As with network equipment in general, GUIs may be preferred to command line interface (CLI) methods of configuration and control.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] With a global view of network status, a controller that manages SD-WAN can perform careful and adaptive traffic engineering by assigning new transfer requests according to current usage of resources (links).
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] For example, this can be achieved by performing central calculation of transmission rates at the controller and rate-limiting at the senders (end-points) according to such rates.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] With SASE, SD-WAN is combined with other network and security technologies including cloud access security broker (CASB), Secure Web Gateway, Data Loss Prevention (DLP), Zero Trust Network Access (ZTNA), Firewall, and other capabilities to connect and protect users and applications.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN and SASE architectures are increasingly used by multinational organizations to improve application performance, simplify global connectivity, and support hybrid work environments across distributed enterprise locations.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] In December 2021, Gartner research firm estimated that by 2025, 50% of SD-WAN purchases will be part of a single vendor SASE offering.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] There are some similarities between SD-WAN and WAN optimization, the name given to the collection of techniques used to increase data-transfer efficiencies across WANs.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] An SD-WAN utilizing virtualization techniques assisted with WAN Optimization traffic control allows network bandwidth to dynamically grow or shrink as needed.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN technology and WAN optimization can be used separately or together, and some SD-WAN vendors are adding WAN optimization features to their products.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] A WAN edge router is a device that routes data packets between different WAN locations, giving enterprise access to a carrier network.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Also called a boundary router, it is unlike a core router, which only sends packets within a single network.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WANs can work as an overlay to simplify the management of existing WAN edge routers, by lowering dependence on routing protocols.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN can also potentially be an alternative to WAN Edge routers.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WANs are similar to hybrid WANs, and sometimes the terms are used interchangeably, but they are not identical.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] A hybrid WAN consists of different connection types, and may have a software defined network (SDN) component, but doesn't have to.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Cloud-based SD-WAN offers advanced features, such as enhanced security, seamless cloud, and support for mobile users, that result naturally from the use of cloud infrastructure.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] As a result, cloud-based SD-WAN can replace MPLS, enabling organizations to release resources once tied to WAN investments and create new capabilities.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Many organizations adopt hybrid WAN strategies that combine MPLS, broadband internet, and wireless connectivity to balance performance, resilience, and cost efficiency during network modernization initiatives.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] An overview discussing three typical reasons to compare MPLS with SD-WAN.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Specifically where IT teams need to retain MPLS due to contract commitments and where the Enterprise migrates from MPLS to an Internet-based SD-WAN.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] As there is no standard algorithm for SD-WAN controllers, device manufacturers each use their own proprietary algorithm in the transmission of data.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] These algorithms determine which traffic to direct over which link and when to switch traffic from one link to another.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Given the breadth of options available in relation to both software and hardware SD-WAN control solutions, it's imperative they be tested and validated under real-world conditions within a lab setting prior to deployment.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] There are multiple solutions available for testing purposes, ranging from purpose-built network emulation appliances which can apply specified network impairments to the network being tested in order to reliably validate performance, to software-based solutions.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] The global SD-WAN market stood at $3.25 billion in 2021 and the market is expected to grow 30% in 2022.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] According to SD-WAN market Report Datavagyanik, North America accounted for more than 77% of the market.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Alternatively, a market overview by Nemertes Research groups SD-WAN vendors into categories based on their original technology space, and which are "Pure-play SD-WAN providers", "WAN optimization vendors", "Link-aggregation vendors", and "General network vendors".
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] While Network World's second category (startups focused specifically on the SD-WAN market), is generally equivalent to Nemertes' "Pure-play SD-WAN providers" category, Nemertes offers a more detailed view of the preexisting WAN and overall networking providers.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Additionally, Nemertes Research also describes the in-net side of the SD-WAN market, describing the go-to-market strategy of connectivity providers entering the SD-WAN market.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] These providers include "Network-as-a-service vendors", "Carriers or telcos", "Content delivery networks" and "Secure WAN providers".
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] MEF 70 standardizes SD-WAN service attributes and uses standard IPv4 and IPv6 routing protocols.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] SD-WAN services also use standard IPsec encryption protocols.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] Additional standardization for other SD-WAN functions and related security functionality not covered in MEF 70 are under development at the MEF Forum.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] There are several opensource SD-WAN solutions and opensource SD-WAN implementations available.
[src:sd-wan/sd-wan] For example, the Linux Foundation has three projects that intersect with and help the SD-WAN market: ONAP, OpenDaylight Project, and the Tungsten Fabric (formerly Juniper Networks' OpenContrail).
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] IT planning for cloud services must be performed in an environment of increased security, compliance and auditing requirements, along with business reorganizations, consolidations and mergers that can rapidly change assumptions.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Providing self-service provisioning, whether in a private or public cloud, requires elastic scaling of computing, storage and network resources, ideally from a common viewpoint and with a common suite of tools.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] requires massive parallel processing on thousands of servers, all of which need direct connections to each other.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] is fueling a constant demand for additional network capacity in the data center.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Operators of hyperscale data center networks face the daunting task of scaling the network to previously unimaginable size, maintaining any-to-any connectivity within a limited budget.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] emerged, the need for larger data centers has increased the energy consumption of those facilities.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] applying existing routing techniques to dynamically adjust the network data plane to save energy.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Also techniques to improve control plane energy efficiency are being researched.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In addition, they may consume an abstracted view of the network for their internal decision-making purposes.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:sd-wan/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] A **wide area network** (**WAN**) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Wide area networks are often established with leased telecommunication circuits.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Businesses, as well as schools and government entities, use wide area networks to relay data to staff, students, clients, buyers and suppliers from various locations around the world.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] In essence, this mode of telecommunication allows a business to effectively carry out its daily functions regardless of location.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Many WANs are, however, built for one particular organization and are private.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] WANs can be separated from local area networks (LANs) in that the latter refers to physically proximal networks.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] The textbook definition of a WAN is a computer network spanning regions, countries, or even the world.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] However, in terms of the application of communication protocols and concepts, it may be best to view WANs as computer networking technologies used to transmit data over long distances, and between different networks.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] WANs are used to connect LANs and other types of networks together so that users and computers in one location can communicate with users and computers in other locations.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Many WANs are built for one particular organization and are private.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Others, built by Internet service providers, provide connections from an organization's LAN to the Internet.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] WANs are often built using leased lines.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] At each end of the leased line, a router connects the LAN on one side with a second router within the LAN on the other.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Because leased lines can be very expensive, instead of using leased lines, WANs can also be built using less costly circuit switching or packet switching methods.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Network protocols, including TCP/IP, deliver transport and addressing functions.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Protocols including Packet over SONET/SDH, Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Frame Relay are often used by service providers to deliver the links that are used in WANs.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] It is also possible to build a WAN with Ethernet.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Academic research into wide area networks can be broken down into three areas: mathematical models, network emulation, and network simulation.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Performance improvements are sometimes delivered via wide area file services or WAN optimization.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Of the approximately four billion addresses defined in IPv4, about 18 million addresses in three ranges are reserved for use in private networks.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Packets addressed in these ranges are not routable on the public Internet; they are ignored by all public routers.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Therefore, private hosts cannot directly communicate with public networks, but require network address translation at a routing gateway for this purpose.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Additionally, encapsulated packets may be encrypted to secure their data.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Many technologies are available for wide-area network links.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Examples include circuit-switched telephone lines, radio wave transmission, and optical fiber.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] New developments have successively increased transmission rates.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] 1960, a 110 bit/s line was normal on the edge of the WAN, while core links of 56 or 64 kbit/s were considered fast.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Today, households are connected to the Internet with dial-up, asymmetric digital subscriber line (ADSL), cable, WiMAX, cellular network or fiber.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] The speeds that people can currently use range from 28.8 kbit/s through a 28K modem over a telephone connection to speeds as high as 100 Gbit/s using 100 Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] The following communication and networking technologies have been used to implement WANs.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] AT&T conducted trials in 2017 for business use of 400-gigabit Ethernet.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Researchers Robert Maher, Alex Alvarado, Domaniç Lavery, and Polina Bayvel of University College London were able to increase networking speeds to 1.125 terabits per second.
[src:sd-wan/wide-area-network] Christos Santis, graduate student Scott Steger, Amnon Yariv, Martin and Eileen Summerfield developed a new laser that potentially quadruples transfer speeds with fiber optics.
